Comment in
    doi: 10.1183/16000617.0041-2017.

Comment in
    doi: 10.1183/16000617.0007-2017.

Pulmonary hypertension (PH) with complicating chronic lung diseases and/or 
hypoxia falls into group 3 of the updated classification of PH. Patients with 
chronic obstructive lung disease (COPD), diffuse lung disease (such as 
idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF)) and with sleep disordered breathing are 
particularly exposed to the risk of developing PH. Although PH in such a context 
is usually mild, a minority of patients exhibit severe haemodynamic impairment, 
defined by a mean pulmonary arterial pressure (mPAP) of ≥35 mmHg or mPAP values 
ranging between 25 mmHg and 35 mmHg with a low cardiac index (<2 L·min-1·m-2). 
The overlap between lung parenchymal disease and PH heavily affects life 
expectancy in such a patient population and complicates their therapeutic 
management. In this review we illustrate the pathological features and the 
underlying pathophysiological mechanisms of pulmonary circulation in chronic 
lung diseases, with an emphasis on COPD, IPF and obstructive sleep apnoea 
syndrome.

